<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Restricted combat initiation is a Very Bad idea.</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?wallace">wallace</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 3:00 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Restricted combat initiation is a Very Bad idea.<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=382" TARGET=_self>Restricted combat initiation is a Very Bad idea.</A> (Min)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> I've seen some suggestions which talked about a system which let

<BR>&gt; group A or player A initiate combat with B but not the other way
<BR>&gt; around(B is generally higher). I think this is a very bad idea
<BR>&gt; because being able to get off the 1st spell without retaliation
<BR>&gt; is too great an advantage even for the lower player(I think most
<BR>&gt; of you who've seen a lot of pk would agree with me). If 2
<BR>&gt; players are allowed to fight each other, let them both be able
<BR>&gt; to initiate combat.
<P>I totally agree with this post, but I must add a thought to it. I think it would be very fitting if the aggressor (person that swings first) be held accountable for the attack. By this I mean the attacker must face the consequences of the local justice system. The defender, even if he wins the confrontation, should not suffer an ill effect from the justice system, since all they were doing is defending themselves. Unfortunately this would not account for harassment, where player A harasses player B unrelentingly until player B swings first. Thus player A was really the aggressor. Not sure how to solve this scenario except by (ignoring playername)
<P>-wallace
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
